name: Phytolith
notes: Summer 2020: go in as "Plantae indet.", "phytolith" as a comment? Deal with later, ask Ellen and co LL: yes, ask Ellen's phytolith friend. JAS emailed Caroline Stromberg about this: "'Phytolith' is listed in a few of the taxa lists of various drilling expeditions, and I was wondering if the 'Poaceae indet.' would be the formal taxonomic name? Or do other non-grasses make phytoliths, and so we would need to coarsen up to a higher taxonomic group?"  from Caroline: "Poaceae indet.” would not be correct, since not all phytoliths are produced by grasses (although the likelihood is reasonably great if near a region with a lot of grasslands). "Plantae indet.” would be better. So, coarse!"  -- given this, put "phytolith" in quotes, rather than "Plantae indet."

name: Euchitonia furcata/elegans
notes: Summer 2020: IDK these; deal with later? LL: This is weird. These were considered two species and a group; however, it looks like Echitonia elegans-furcata is now a species name (see WoRMS); AF that's bizarre, but i guess we follow worms in that case. PBDB structure does not currently allow any non-alphabetic characters in species name, i.e., no "/" or "-" BUT  the Taxonomy Team can change this Winter 2021: from David Lazarus hyphen - that’s what we arbitrarily chose in NSB. AF: So this is an issue to raise, as is Botryostrobus auritus-australis; in PBDB, so it will be classified correctly

name: Bortyostrobus auritus/australis
notes: Summer 2020: IDK these; deal with later? LL: B. auritus-australis is an accepted name (see WoRMS); AF what's with these, that's no sort of formal taxonomy i'm used to. Winter 2021: From David Lazarus: Best call this 'Euchitonia elegans/furcata group’  for now. It is in NSB at the moment as a valid taxon [id 2004045]. Some people believe furcata and elegans can be distinguished but others do not understand how.  So currently ‘elegans’ and ‘furcata’ by themselves are given as synonyms for the ‘group’ version in NSB.  Not elegan[t]\s but that’s what we’ve got.
